                    <TextBlock TextAlignment="Center" FontSize="48" Foreground="white" Canvas.Left="12" Canvas.Top="10">
                                What are chord progressions?
                    </TextBlock>
                    <TextBlock  FontSize="30" Foreground="White" Canvas.Left="12" Canvas.Top="117">
                        
                        Chord progressions are series of two or more chords used in a piece of music.
                        <LineBreak/>
                        The chords in a progression are represented by roman numerals and are determined by key. 
                        <LineBreak/>
                        For example:
                    </TextBlock>
                    <TextBlock TextAlignment="Center" FontSize="48" Foreground="white" Canvas.Left="12" Canvas.Top="237">
                                I ->  IV -> V
                    </TextBlock>
                    <TextBlock  FontSize="30" Foreground="White" Canvas.Left="12" Canvas.Top="306">
                        In this example, if you pick C as the root note of the first chord, the progression goes 'C Major' (the root), to 'F Major'
                        <LineBreak/>
                        (F is a fourth up from C), to 'G Major' (G is a Fifth up from C).
                    </TextBlock>
                    <TextBlock TextAlignment="Center" FontSize="48" Foreground="white" Canvas.Left="12" Canvas.Top="386">
                                I ->  III -> IV -> Iv
                    </TextBlock>
                    <TextBlock  FontSize="30" Foreground="White" Canvas.Left="12" Canvas.Top="450">
                        In this example, if you pick C as the root note of chord I, the progression goes 'C Major' (the root), to 'E Major'
                        <LineBreak/>
                        (E is a third up from C), to 'F Major' (F is a fourth up from C), to 'F minor' (the minor or  major chords are diferentiated by
                        <LineBreak/>
                         the case of the roman numerals).
                        <LineBreak/>
                        <LineBreak/>
                        One major or minor chord can’t do much storytelling on their own. But even simple, repetitive progressions 
                        <LineBreak/>
                        of chords have the power to convey a complex array of emotions and musical ideas.
                        <LineBreak/>
                        <LineBreak/>
                        There are happy chord progressions, sad chord progressions, simple chord progressions and very complex 
                        chord progressions.
                    </TextBlock>
                </Canvas>
                <Canvas Visibility="Hidden" Name="Teo2" Height="886" Width="1712" Background="#33000000" Canvas.Left="104" Canvas.Top="97">
